The question becomes: Is it safe to do pointer arithmetic (`object += s->size`) on an object pointer modified by `setup_object`? The important point is that `setup_object` (and thus `kasan_init_slab_obj`) might return a *tagged* pointer because of KASAN. We need to be sure that adding `s->size` to a tagged pointer is correct. If the pointer has been tagged by KASAN, it is important to remember that KASAN's tags are stored in the top byte of the pointer (ARM64 HW MTE) or SW tags. Thus, `p + s->size` simply has the same tag. The subsequent call to `setup_object` is responsible for resetting the tag before assigning a new one. I think this is safe, because `kasan_init_slab_obj` internally will probably reset the tag before assigning a new one. The same logic is used in `allocate_slab` when building the freelist. So, KASAN tagging and pointer arithmetic are consistent. I think we're good.


