The code's intention seems sound: skip `set_freepointer`, `get_freepointer`, and `shuffle_freelist`, so no need to track which objects are free within the slab. Makes sense for speed. However, I went through multiple questions. Is it safe to skip building a freelist? Does it matter if `__GFP_ZERO` is passed? What about KASAN and memory initialization? What if the object's freepointer is located outside the object payload? Are there any potential KASAN splats when accessing possibly poisoned memory during initialization? This required going through many SLUB internals.

